<td width="83%" class="lighttable">
<br />
<font class="post">
--Now we come to the heart of the matter, the current tale of treachery and woe.  A continuation of the 'To Sift Through Bitter Ashes' arc--those events which follow Animus de Nova, Creo Igneum, and The Lectures to an Empty Hall, the current arc takes place just after the invasion of Befallen and begins only days before Cazic-Thules assault upon Lesser Fey.--<br><br>T'enel absentmindedly brushed his cheek with the smooth silk of his dining gloves.  The sensation was soothing but did little to ease the growing tension in his gut.  Too many plans were too close to fruition for the Teir'Dal Lord to take pleasure from his small indulgences.<br><br>"Take it away," he sighed, gesturing at the silvered dishes heaped with food that covered the table before him.  "Poison it and then throw it into the streets."  He sat with affected disinterest as the menial's cleared the meal, restless but weary, jaded with ennui.  Once the servants had gone, T'enel waited in silence, stroking the flesh of his eye socket, letting the sensation lull him into a temporary distraction.<br><br>"Will there be anything else, your Lordship?"  The speaker was T'veren, his seneschal and one of the few of his house allowed to speak directly to T'enel.<br><br>"I do not think that I like winning," T'enel said by way of answer.<br><br>"Understandable, m'lord.  Once this small matter has been resolved, perhaps a new challenge will arise worthy of your talents.  This is but a lull, nothing to be troubled at.  Might I suggest that you allow yourself to savor these final moments of the game, luxuriate in your victory, m'lord.  It has, after all, been decades in the achieving."<br><br>"Perhaps.  Yes, I suppose you are correct.  You usually are.  How fairs her ladyship?"<br><br>The manservant coughed discretely to cover his distress at the question before answering in carefully measured tones.  "The Lady T'enel is in fine health.  The other lady is…unchanged in her condition."<br><br>T'enel laughed, a harsh barking sound with no real humor.  "Your tact does you credit.  In other words, my wife is her usual shrewish self and taking it out on the servants will our little caged bird not only does not sing, but is slowly dying."<br><br>"An adequate presumption, m'lord."<br><br>"We must keep her alive a bit longer, Veren.  It would hardly do if she were to fade with a family reunion so close to hand."  He permitted himself a predatory grimace.  "Why, to see her daughter in chains would most certainly break her heart.  I can't have her missing that, can I?  After all she has done for me, it is the least I can do."<br><br>"Regarding that, if I may, m'lord."<br><br>"By all means."<br><br>"It has been brought to my attention that delivery of the Mayong's gifts has been delayed."<br><br>T'enel surged to his feet, overturning his chair in the process.  "Unacceptable," he growled.<br><br>T'veren continued speaking as if uninterrupted.  "The menial Dranerius has cited difficulties with the handling of the animals.  I have taken the liberty of having the handler that the Mayong sent with them summoned.  He awaits the pleasure of your audience."<br><br>High Lord T'enel stripped the white silk from his hands and tossed the gloves to the floor.  "By all means, let us go speak with this lowly," he replied, taking the black leather gloves and ebony cane his seneschal passed into his hands.<br><br>***<br><br>The handler was appropriately genuflective, dropping to his knees as the pair entered, pressing his forehead to stone before the Lord's boots.  T'enel was pleased to see the Mayong's menials followed the proper discipline and dress.  The animal handler's face was covered with a crude leather mask and his body swathed in heavy muslin to spare the nobility the blight of actually seeing the lesser exposed flesh.<br><br>"You may rise and speak freely in his Lordship's presence," T'veren lied politically.  In truth, no menial could ever address a lord with freedom and they were very much aware of the fact.<br><br>The menial rose but kept his eyes appropriately downcast.  "I am at his lordships command."<br><br>"What are you called?" T'veren asked.<br><br>"This one has no name.  His lordship may address this one as anything.  It is ours but to serve."<br><br>"Good, good," mumbled T'enel.  "Well trained.  Now, let me surmise a few things.  As a lowly animal keeper, you must find yourself in a difficult position.  Surely, Dranerius has ordered you to report to no one but him."<br><br>"This is true."<br><br>"And yet you are here."<br><br>"I am.  I was summoned.  It is not mine to refuse."<br><br>"Of course.  So, keeper, if I ask questions of you, will you answer me truthfully, even though you have been ordered otherwise?" T'enel asked liltingly.<br><br>"Yes."  The reply was quick and stern and T'veren sucked in his breath at the breach of etiquette.<br><br>T'enel laughed.  "And why would that be?"<br><br>"This one was given orders by the Lord of Mists.  This one was charged with a duty to deliver beasts and tend them until these beasts passed into the possession of Lord T'enel and to continue in this duty if required.  At no point was this one ever truly the menial Dranerius' to command."  The reply was spoken softly in a matter-of-fact tone but an undercurrent of malice was plain.<br><br>T'enel clapped his hands together in appreciation.  "You see, Veren, the Mayong recognizes the significance of this delivery.  I knew I could rely upon his discretion.  He has sent to us, no simple animal keeper, but a diplomat as well.  And were I to wager, this lowly keeper possesses a few other hidden talents as well."  T'enel addressed the keeper directly.  "I am correct in this?"<br><br>"I am but an humble keeper of beasts, m'lord.  However, you are correct that this one was also chosen from among many.  This one is a noble-blooded crossbreed.  This has given me some affinity with the beasts and a talent for the natural healings."<br><br>"And also given the Mayong a useful agent without arousing strife between houses," T'enel concluded.  "Well played.  Well played indeed.  I will require your continued service, at that.  I have certain 'beasts' that are indeed in need of natural healings.  Oh, Veren, this works out very well.  But tell me, keeper, why has my shipment been delays?  The truth, not Dranerius' lies."<br><br>The keeper hesitated before speaking.  "This one would, before speaking, wonder at his own place within the world."<br><br>"I have already said you will take service within this house.  What more do you require?  I do not bargain with servants."<br><br>"Of course, m'lord.  This one asks only a small boon, an accommodation of an old superstition."<br><br>T'enel arched an eyebrow in surprise.  The Mayong had, indeed, sent him a package filled with surprises.  "So, you are not just a keeper of animals but a keeper of the dead as well?  I had thought that order long extinct.  Still, such misguided necromancy would explain your skills in healing."<br><br>"As your lordship says."<br><br>"Very well then.  It's not as if there is any meaning to the old superstitions.  By Innoruuk I swear, I shall not eat of the dead of my family.  Are you satisfied now, keeper?"<br><br>"I am, m'lord."<br><br>"Then tell me why my presents are being withheld."<br><br>"Dranerius has seen fit to give Lord Rileaus use of your menagerie."<br><br>***<br><br>T'enel stormed through the halls of the House, striking columns with his cane in anger as he passed them.  T'veren was forced into a near-run to keep pace.<br><br>"Hit him with everything we have.  I want him dead.  I want his house burned.  I want the land salted.  I want no two stones left on top of each other and I want his head on a pike."<br><br>"Dranerius or Rileaus, m'lord."<br><br>"Yes!  And do it now.  Tonight.  Kill everyone but the girl and bring her directly to me.  You will see to this personally."<br><br>"Of course, m'lord."<br><br>"Wait.  Do not kill them all.  Spare his oldest son.  I will adopt him and prevent any challenge to my acquisition of Rileaus' holdings.  Kill the rest but bring me that one.  I've enough enemies, I'll not give them a martyred house as well.  Is this understood?"<br><br>"Completely, m'lord, and wise."<br><br>"Do this then for me."<br>


