<td width="83%" class="lighttable">
<br />
<font class="post">
All things trend to entropy and the center can not hold.<br><br>Across a wooden desk, rolling, a river pebble, smooth, like amber, like a tear not-quite-shed.<br><br>"I am the Fire Caller and I summon Tunare to me."<br><br><br><br>'…the cruelest month, breeding lilacs out of the dead land, mixing memory and desire…'<br><br><br><br>*Mistmoore has broken the ban and is moving troops and supplies through fey land. The Court of Tunare is at war with the Krom and has called on the Fey to provide aid and support.*<br><br>A ridge on the desk, rolling, direction changes, toward an edge.<br><br>"I am the Wind Caller and I summon Tunare to me."<br><br>Fate withdraws her claws from a waiting paladin, she hunts elsewhere this day.<br><br>*Only the fey still hold the old ties, where else could she have retreated to?*<br><br>A primal force, raw and ill-formed, an avatar of fear tears through the once silent wood, seeking, hunting.<br><br>"I am the Earth Caller and I summon Tunare to me."<br><br>To the edge, rolling, grinding like a mill stone, irresistible force.<br><br><br><br>'Because these wings are no longer wings to fly but merely vans to beat the air, the air which is now thoroughly small and dry, smaller and dryer than the will, teach us to care and not to care, teach us to sit still. Pray for us sinners now and at the hour of our death. Pray for us now and at the hour of our death.'<br><br><br><br>Flame danced across parapets of House Rileaus. The fortifications broke, men died, lords died, the house shivered to its foundation under the assault.<br><br>*Remember Dessy: In transience, meaning*<br><br>Rolling, the sound a soft growl of stone, a whimper, not a bang.<br><br>"I am the Wave Caller and I summon Tunare to me."<br><br>In the bowels of House T'enel, the scrap of broom on stone, the cleaning of stalls, the quiet work of a menial, a servant serves. Silver cages for gilded birds or is it the other way 'round?<br><br>An amber pebble quivers for a moment on the lip of the desk.<br><br>"I am here."<br><br>The gods war on earth and, in the heavens, there is peace. The forest fragments like shards of discarded mirrors and the fey war openly for the first time since the Sundering.<br><br>*Augre, we have to get out of here* Almost fifty and still running.<br><br>The unicorn's horn corrupted, severed clean, innocence is no more. The Primal Fear rescinds, a final vengeance tossed behind in caprice. The Tunare cares not, the tiny fey are below her notice. It is the way of gods--consumption.<br><br>The pebble hangs, stretches, drops, an amber tear falling toward the stone.<br><br>"A final curse before I go."<br><br><br><br>'I will show you fear in a handful of dust.'<br><br><br><br>The fey burn out like motes of fire in the god's eye. Eons lost in the blink of an eye. In the wake of horror passing, their twisted forms rise again and nothing is as it ever will be again. The sky runs red, the red of blood, not fire.<br><br>*The Ancient is where he is most needed at any time. Absence, in your case, my darling boy, is an excuse. Only destiny is responsible.* Small comfort grown smaller, Fey court in exile, in only.<br><br><br><br>'Till the wind shake a thousand whispers from the yew. And after this, our exile.'<br><br><br><br>Stone to stone, a shattering of amber, a spray of splinters and flashing images without an audience, fragments of times lost.<br><br>The broom stops its sweeping. Flesh, too, falls to stone. Hearts shatter too.<br><br>Waves of amber spread across House Rileaus, perhaps across Norrath, and time stopped, leaving the world frozen in a moment.<br><br>All but one. Perhaps because the pebble was attuned to her, perhaps because some agency was watching over her, perhaps because, in a world newly devoid of innocence, reasons no longer mattered either--Carezzia found herself in a world of living statues, wandering in the fraction of the second. She tugged at Augre's arm and found him as immobile as the rest.<br><br><br><br>'Dry bones can harm no one…In a flash of lightning. Then a damp gust bringing rain…then spoke the thunder…'<br><br><br><br>"Go," sighed a voice, a whisper of wind in leaves. No speaker was in sight and the sound was just behind her ears. "Leave this place. She waits for you outside, for you and for him…her him. Tell her that I am not finished forging the Ancient. She is Destiny; she will understand."<br><br>Carezzia turned in circles, looking for the speaker, looking for answers. Neither were to be found and she made her way from the burning building, out, from a time-frozen Neriak to the dark forests of the hillsides around. "A dream," she whispered to herself. "Like living in a dream…a waking dream." Here and there around her, the sleepers move sluggishly and seem to be slowly wakening. She hurries to the woods.<br><br><br><br>'You gave me hyacinths first a year ago…Yet when we came back, late, from the hyacinth garden, your arms full, your hair wet, I could not speak, and my eyes failed, I was neither living nor dead, and I knew nothing, looking into the heart of light, the silence.'<br><br><br><br>Destiny waits there, Dark and oppressive like a gathering store. Eyes blazing violet hues, robes snapping in a non-existent wind. A dark black panther stalks about her feet, weaving, menacing, complimenting the ominous image then suddenly an over-grown kitten, pressing against its long-absent master, purring. "It's time to go," growled the brewing storm.<br><br><br><br>'A woman drew her long black hair out tight and fiddled whisper music on those strings and bats with baby faces in the violet light whistled and beat their wings…"<br><br><br><br>[Religious scholars have debated at length on the significance of the battle between Tunare and Cazic-Thule for dominion of Lesser Fey. They have debated the underlying cause of the conflict and they have debated how, if Tunare won the encounter as her followers claim, Cazic-Thule was able to claim the forests as his own. <br><br>They have not, predictably, considered the implications of this conflict to the denizens of the land, nor why this region became their chosen battleground. Such trivial concerns are beneath the consideration of liturgical grey-beards. Neither have they considered why, of all the forest's denizens, the brownies remain completely unaffected. <br><br>Completely lost to all concerned was the question of what, if any, actions were taken by Karana. As always, the Stormlord's motives and interests remain unknown and unquestioned.]<br><br><br><br>ooc-Yes, the references and overtones are deliberate and you spend too much time reading old poetry. <br>


