<td width="83%" class="lighttable">
<br />
<font class="post">
The tree was good for hunting: high for the launch, good overhang on the game trail, a solid grip to the bark. The leaves cast deep shadow and prey rarely looked up.<br><br>This one was loud, singing out its presence well in advance of its approach--an easy, lazy hunt--tense, coil, spring…<br><br>The bard twisted at the last moment and the cat's teeth closed on cloth instead of his throat. The animal's weight bowled him forward and claws raked deeply into the muscles of his shoulders. The bard tried to crawl free and the cat's hind paws hammered into the small of his back, driving the breath from him.<br><br>As abruptly as it had come, the attacker was gone and the bard scrambled to his feet. A frantic glance revealed a wood elf wrestling with a black panther as large as she was and the bard chose the second course of valor--he ran.<br><br>Carezzia shoved her cat away and stood. "What are you doing?" she shouted at it in frustration but the cat's only reply was a disdainful gaze before it began to lick the blood from its fur.<br><br>/you know what it's doing…<br>…pretty birds, feline prey, the natural order/<br>/you feel it too…<br>…the hunt, the taste of blood, the culling of the weak/<br>/prey is given…<br>…prey is taken/<br><br>"Shut up! Just leave me alone!" she yelled at the whispering voices in her mind and sank to the grass, cradling her head in her hands. This was not what she had expected from adulthood, not what she wanted from freedom. Her life was spiraling out of control and all she wanted to do was go home, wherever that was.<br><br>/you are home…<br>…you are always home/<br>/you suffer because you deny your nature…<br>…you will suffer until you understand your nature/<br><br>The elf ignored the whispers and laid back on the ground, staring up at the boughs of the fog-shrouded trees of Toxxulia.<br><br>Her mentor and surrogate father, Quildluane, had died. That was surely the beginning of the end for her childhood, although she had not suspected it at the time. His passing had brought her full circle, back to a mystery of absent parents and estranged relatives, back to the confusion and insecurities of an overly-sheltered upbringing, and, physically, back to the quiet forests of Lesser Faydwer. It had been a chance to take control of her life, to settle the past and answer a few nagging personal questions. Nothing had been right since.<br><br>Her visit to Quildluane's house had attracted the attention of the fairy court itself and prompted an audience with Joleena herself--a meeting which yielded no answers and even more mysteries. She had moved on to Kelethin where her inquiries had triggered highly placed agents of the Teir'Dal--agents that had been in place for decades--and had led to her kidnapping.<br><br>It was when she had been smuggled in chains to Freeport that she had begun to experiment with the newfound charms of her body, with mixed results. The internal politics of the Teir'Dal nobility was complex beyond her understanding and other, external, forces seemed to be at work as well.<br><br>Her awkward seductions had delayed her delivery to her intended captor, placing her, instead, in the home of another Teir'Dal noble. It was there, perfumed, pampered, and drugged, that she had attempted a clumsy escape, attempting to avoid a foul ceremony where she was to be either s sexual servant or living sacrifice--she was unsure which, perhaps both.<br><br>Her memories of her escape were confused and indistinct, an after-effect of the drugging, but she knew that she should never have been successful on her own. There had been an attack during her escape, Teir'Dal against Teir'Dal, and the 'servant class' had been largely ignored in the bloody conflict. Even then, she would have been recaptured eventually had it not been for the Fey.<br><br>The Princess Joleena had given Carezzia a token, little more than a pebble really, but Carezzia had taken great pains to keep the gift with her, even through her captivity. She would learn later that, even as she struggled to find her way free of the Teir'Dal, the gods themselves fought in Lesser Faydwer. When Cazic-Thule cursed and blighted the Fey, the stone had shattered, stranding the lost wood elf temporarily outside of time, free to escape while those about her were frozen in the moment.<br><br>That was the first time she had heard the voices, soft whispers urging her to move toward her destiny, telling her when to turn, which stairs to take, the paths to follow until she was at last free of the dark maze that was Neriak, long gone before time sluggishly resumed.<br><br>The Erudian had been waiting for her as if by plan, Carezzia's cat alongside like a living symbol of reassurance. When the Erudian had opened a rift in space, the wood elf had followed meekly--to Toxxulia.<br><br>The Erudian had proven to be the latest in a long string of mysteries. Carezzia's new keeper spoke little and said even less. She had silently nursed the elf through the after-effects of the drug and the physical hurts of her captivity. Beyond that, Carezzia was left to wander the forest alone or with only the cat for company.<br><br>But she was not alone, not with the voices that whispered softly in the back of her mind.<br><br>"Bat wings."<br><br>Carezzia startled out of her revelry and found herself staring up into the Erudian's dispassionate gaze.<br><br>"And fish. Then we talk." The Erudian turned crisply and stalked out of sight, toward the empty building where she slept.<br><br>Carezzia stood and favored the cat with an expansive shrug of her shoulders. "I guess we need bat wings."<br><br>***<br><br>T'Veren pushed the door closed with his heal and crossed the waiting room to sit next to its only other occupant. "News from the Council, High Lord?"<br><br>T'Ere T'Enel shook his head. "They are still pretending to deliberate. Make no mistake, Veren, I have many enemies among the noble houses but the law is clear. For now, their hands are tied."<br><br>"What about the son?"<br><br>"Troublesome that." T'Enel frowned. "I did give specific orders to spare the oldest son for adoption."<br><br>T'Veren remained silent. Rileaus' oldest son had refused to be taken alive and had proven to be a capable as well. In the end, T'Veren had ordered the younger son taken instead and put a crossbow bolt through the eldest.<br><br>"They'll place the surviving boy as my ward and use him to lever Rileaus' properties away from me when he matures. It is an acceptable cost. I've eliminated another house, for a decade at least, and the other houses have their hands tied. They make not like it but he gave me just cause. It's still poor repayment for the loss of the girl."<br><br>T'Veren nodded. "The prophets have found traces of Fey magics but little else. She appears to have completely vanished during the conflict."<br><br>"Why am I not surprised to find the Fey still involved? I suppose an offense against their gods is not easily forgotten."<br><br>"Even if it fails," T'Veren noted.<br><br>"I'll have my due. That's why I summoned you: any change in her condition?"<br><br>"No, m'lord. The priests can't heal her--in that at least Tunare still protects her. It's a slow process but she's dying."<br><br>"Ideas?"<br><br>"We could release her for a time and then recapture her when she's recovered. It's fairly clear that captivity and Neriak themselves are what is sapping her life. We could also try moving her to a different location for a time."<br><br>"Given all the problems with the daughter, I don't think moving her out of the city is wise. I'd rather see her die than lose her completely."<br><br>T'Veren nodded. "Then we're out of options."<br><br>"Maybe. Move her to the warrens. After all, how different is she from an animal. Oh, and have the Keeper added to my retinue where I can keep an eye on him."<br><br>"As you order. By tomorrow?" T'Veren asked, gesturing toward the closed door leading to the council chamber.<br><br>"Tonight. They can't put me off much longer."<br><br>***<br><br>Lady Evengel T'Enel watched the water cascade from the fountain as if it were the most fascinating thing in the universe. Her hand mindlessly caressed the large hound at her side and sporadically she would pass it a small pastry or sugared treat from the tray beside her. She was known to spend hours here in her underground garden, hiding from the burdens of her house and avoiding the cold sorrow of facing a disinterested, preoccupied husband.<br><br>A maid entered and knelt, unseen behind the Lady T'Enel. "The boy has arrived, m'lady."<br><br>"Rileaus' survivor?"<br><br>"Yes, ma'am."<br><br>"Give him a room and assign him a retainer. Leave me."<br><br>"Yes, ma'am."<br><br>"Wait!" snapped Evengel, raising her hand. "How old is he?"<br><br>"Fourteen, I believe, m'lady."<br><br>"Fourteen. My own son would have been sixteen had he lived," Evengel said in a tone barely stronger than a sigh then raising her voice she added, "Bring him to me. I would see this new child of the house."<br><br>


