<td width="83%" class="lighttable">
<br />
<font class="post">
ooc: Some of the more observant may have noticed that Carezzia's cat has grown from a fuzzy golden kitten to a menacing black panther. That is intentional, I have been using the cat as a visual metaphor for Care's internal, personal developement.)<br><br><br>"Batwings," announced Carezzia, dropping them in a heap on the stone floor. "And fish," she concluded, laying a still flopping stringer beside the heap. The Erudian glanced up briefly and returned to assembling what appeared to be a portable spit. It was the only furnishing other than a spartan bedroll which Carezzia had ever seen the Eruidian employ within the barren building. The house was so empty that Carezzia had found she felt less exposed outside in the forest than inside its walls.<br><br>"Who are you?" the Erudian demanded abruptly.<br><br>"Carezzia Maj…"<br><br>"What are you?" came the interruption.<br><br>"I am a druid of Tunare, but…"<br><br>"Then why are you special?"<br><br>Carezzia took an involuntary step backward. "I don't understand what you are after."<br><br>"Roll the fish in the batwings and stack them here by the spit. For some reason, you are important enough to attract the attention of serious powers of both the High Lords of Neriak and the Fey Court. Tell me why."<br><br>"I don't know."<br><br>/don't you?…<br>…the sins of the father befall his children/<br><br>The Erudian fixed her with a piercing stare then turned back to the spit. "Creo Ignium," she whispered and the interior of the small over was alive with flame. "What do ou know of the history of your guild?"<br><br>Carezzia struggled to keep pace with the changing focus of the inquisition. "The Order was founded by Aelric…" Again she was interrupted, this time by a loud snort of derision.<br><br>"Aelric the Absent. Aelric the Selfish and the Proud." The venom in the Erudian's tone was unmistakable and frightening. It held to promise of imminent violence. "Four men! Four men build that house and he wasn't one of them!<br><br>"They were like brothers--Arturo, Azimuth, Kaolinn, and Descourge--all dedicated to the same goal, all united. They are your history. I don't give a tinkers damn for the first three but they've never failed the family and they have never, ever, failed Des when he needed them. Not many people can say that, not even his own family." The Erudian fell suddenly silent, leaving Carezzia struggling to place the outburst in context.<br><br>The Erudian poked at the coals of the fire and, apparently satisfied with what she found, began to place the fish rolls into the spit. "He's not going back to the Order, not again."<br><br>"Who?" asked Carezzia, still a bit lost in the conversation.<br><br>"Almost a month ago, Descourge went into Neriak, partially to save you, partially for his own reasons. When he returns, if he returns, he is mine. I've waited decades, supporting him, helping him to pursue his vision of a better way of life. I've watched them break his heart again and again and still he goes back. No more. He's earned his rest…I've earned his rest. It's time for a real home, for him and for me. It's time for others to help him instead of the other way around. Enough chasing the dream, it's time he came home to his family. Selfish, I know, but…"<br><br>/she is lonely, she misses her partner…<br>…it is her right to ask/<br><br>The Erudian's voice trailed to silence until Carezzia prompted, "What does this have to do with me?"<br><br>"Calculated risk. That Ancient of Days is blessed and cursed to always be exactly where he is most needed when he is most needed. Your paths have crossed too often and now you leave Neriak even as he goes in. Deny it if you wish but I have to trust his instincts on this. That mean trusting you.<br><br>"There is nothing wrong with his vision. The dreams and philosophies that he has championed for so long are reasonable, if naïve. They have not failed not has he failed in them. It is, instead, that the fight for a better way is a permanent one. He may be immortal but he cannot fight alone forever. I cannot wait forever. I also can never ask him to abandon the fight. It is more than his life's work; it is who he is. To ask him to stop would be to betray everything he is and to betray his trust…"<br><br>/she is mistaken, though accurate…<br>…she is his life's work, his greatest achievement/<br><br>"I am asking you to take up his burden, to carry a portion of the load and speak wisdom in his place. You will not be alone. He could no more stop trying than he can stop breathing but he cannot always be first and only any longer. All of the Destined will be here to help but…I don't want him to fight this war alone any longer."<br><br>/tred cautious, she is vulnerable now…<br>…weakness creates aggression/<br><br>"I'm not sure I understand. I don't even know if I can," stammered the wood elf, overwhelmed by the momentum of the moment.<br><br>"Take this." The Erudian passed her a rough, iron-wrought key on a long loop of leather. "It is to his desk in your guild's council room. Read his notes. Consider the matter. There is time yet."<br><br>"I…I will do this."<br><br>/there will be no turning back…<br>…the decision was already made/<br><br>"Good," snapped the Erudian, suddenly brusque again. She turned and began to flip the fish rolls, hissing from the heat, out of the spit and onto the floor in a low mound. As she did, there came a low, insistent scratching at the door. "Let him in before he ruins the woodwork."<br><br>Carezzia opened the door and was nearly knocked from her feet as a stout bundle of fur and energy burst into the room and trundled to the mound of cooling fish rolls. Regaining her balance, she was able to get a clearer look at the new arrival and she began to grin. It was a bear cub and a well-fed one at that. He looked like a barrel with tree stumps for legs all covered in black fur. The bear made a 'whumphling' sound and began to plow through the pile of cooked fish. To Carezzia's surprise, the Erudian knelt and drew the beast into an affectionate embrace and a momentary smile crossed the usually grim face.<br><br>The Erudian stood and faced Carezzia, the smile gone as if it had never existed. "This is Marlowe. He is dumb, weak, and easily distracted. You will treat him with respect and affection for he is a true companion and no simple pet."<br><br>"I do not understand again."<br><br>The Erudian hissed in frustration before speaking. "There is no love lost between the monk Arturo and I but he has always done very well by the Ancient. Frustrated with the persistent, lonely wanderings of his friend, the monk took it upon himself to bring the matter to the attention of the appropriate authorities, shall we say. He fought his way across the Plane of Growth and to Tunare herself to demand a boon. She relented and Arturo insisted that it was not right for the Ancient to be forever alone simply because his duties to the Court demanded that he travel the length and breadth of the world. The result of this was Marlowe--a permanent, bound companion."<br><br>"Then why is he here instead of with Descourge?"<br><br>"Because he is needed here. Do not trouble yourself with matters beyond your station. For now, Marlowe will lead you back to the dustbin you call a guildhall. When you are ready, remember that our ursine friend is especially fond of fish." While the Erudian spoke, the small bear ate the last of the fish and began licking the floor they had lain upon.<br><br>/she does not fully understand either…<br>…there is nothing to understand/<br>/it is a mercy…<br>…it is a mistake mixing hunter and prey/<br>/the two are intrinsically bound, the separation of predator and prey is an illusion…<br>…we are not agreed on this/<br>/it is done…<br>…it is allowed/<br><br>Carezzia was suddenly aware of the Erudian staring at her with a mixture of curiosity and disgust. "You hear them, don't you?"<br><br>"Hear what?"<br><br>"Don't obfuscate. You hear the voices, the susurrus of the wind, the whispering of the trees, call it what you will."<br><br>"I don't know what it is that I hear. I just don't know."<br><br>"Humph. The Ancient hears them as well. It is probably the fey. <br><br>"Marlowe?" the Erudian called to the bear and he turned, his mouth open, tongue lapping the last traces of food from his muzzle. "Take her home."<br><br>The bear gave a contented 'harumph' and a glowing rift appeared before him. With a rolling gait, the bear trotted through and Carezzia hurried behind him.<br><br>***<br><br>For decades, her entire world had been a three foot wide circle of iron, a flat bottomed cage with arching iron bars reaching to a central point, a cold metallic dome. It was almost wide enough to lie down, almost high enough to stand up. Increasingly over the years, her mind would leave her body, flying free to live in memories or hiding in dreams, and she had become used to long periods of lost time. The world outside held only the barest of interests for her.<br><br>This awakening was different--there was light. The Teir'Dal used visible light only rarely, for reading or for workings of extreme detail. Even then, the light was limited, a cluster of candles, an isolated torch or lantern, but nothing like this. Her surroundings were flooded with light, a complete, ambient glow so very different from the shadow-spawning flickers of fire. In truth, the glow was terribly dim but after years trapped in the subterranean blackness of Neriak, it was blinding. She was forced to keep her eyes tightly closed, tears trickling from beneath her lashes.<br><br>While her eyes could not seek, her ears did. The loudest sound was an intermittent scraping, the scratch of metal on stone, but behind it boiled a sea of rustlings, of dragging and walking, breathing, panting, and growling, of life. She heard the click of claws and the hiss of scales, the clack of hooves and the patter of paws. The noises were soft behind the scraping but she heard them and sought more, her mind returning to a long neglected body. She smelled manure and sweat, damp fur and urine, and across it all lay the wonderful perfume of dried hay. Teasing at the edge of her reeling senses, perhaps, barely, she heard a faint humming, the barest lilt of song.<br><br>It was too much. Either she was dead or mad, or, worse yet, her captors had happened upon a new level of creativity and sadism. Light and life--this could not be true…<br><br>It was then that Kathrin Majialenne realized she was no longer in her cage.<br><br>


