<td width="83%" class="lighttable">
<br />
<font class="post">
Kathrin realized the absence of the cage by the pain.  After years spent laying in an unnatural curl, without the cage to bind her, her legs had begun to relax and, as they extended, painful cramps lanced her muscles.  She pulled herself into a tight ball and struggled not to cry out.  Even free, she was still caged.  It could be weeks, even months, before she would be able to lie flat.  As for walking…she refused to consider the dire possibility that the ability might be forever lost.<br><br>To distract herself, she set about learning what she could of her new surroundings, hopefully without betraying her wakefulness to any who might be watching.  The scraping sound seemed closer.<br><br>She pressed a hand downward, shielded from view beneath her body.  She lay on what felt to be a mound of dried cut grasses.  Spears of broken straws poked at her hand as she felt about and found that, only a few inches down, the floor beneath was of cold stone.<br><br>Ignoring her watering eyes and the throbbing of a growing headache, she forced her eyes open to slits and tried to see.  The glowing light was less overwhelming now.  Vision blurred by tears, she made out the rough details of her surroundings.<br><br>Kathrin lay on a crude pallet of straw roughly in the center of a wide but low ceilinged cavern.  Darker alcoves at the cave's edges seemed to serve as stanchions and cells for the menagerie that she could hear but still not see clearly in the glow of the light.  The warm illumination was emitted from paper lanterns which were hung about the uneven cavern walls, filled with fireflies, or, more likely, glowing beetles.<br><br>She was still underground, probably still in Neriak, just deeper.  The realization drained much of the hope she had begun to feel--it was a larger, different type, but a cage nevertheless.<br><br>The scraping noises came again and she twisted cautiously to look toward the source.  At the cavern's darkened edge, a humanoid figure was mucking the alcoves, pitching used straw into a two-wheeled cart, the metal tines of a long fork striking at intervals against the stone of the cavern's floor.  As she watched, her vision gradually adjusting to the light, the figure hefted the twin handles that served as the cart's yoke and dragged it beyond her range of sight.  Minutes later, it returned, the contents of the cart replaced with a bound bundle of straw.  It grunted with effort as it hefted the bale and labored it into the dark stall.  Dropping the bale, the figure struck the bundle with a slashing backhanded motion of its left hand and the bale burst open.  The creature kicked the bale apart then finalized its spreading with the metallic fork.  Though its proportions were humanoid, the creature was stooped and walked with a rolling limp.  Its left hand and lower arm seemed abnormally large, possibly clubbed.<br><br>The creature pulled the cart past Kathrin's pallet and dropped the handles at the entrance of another alcove.  As it passed, she was able to get a closer look at her "companion."  It was draped all about in ill-fitting rags and comically articulated like an animated scarecrow.  For lack of distinguishable characteristics, Kathrin presumed it to be male.  Its face was hidden by a rough leather mask and its eye were covered in a milky film.  Her memory dredged up a half-forgotten tale of orc-Teir'Dal crossbreeds bred as menial slaves for the dark elfin nobility, and she suppressed a shiver.<br><br>Suddenly, the creature straightened to attention, like a dog catching a scent, and it shuffled toward her.  Kathrin pressed her eyes closed and tried to keep her breathing calm and regular, as if she were still asleep.  She heard its heavy treads stop quite near her prone form and it began to speak.<br><br>"I could provide you with a sophoric to assist your sleep and ease your pains, but I am certain you would reject such an offer.  You are in the warrens below the House T'Enel, the place where the High Lord retains his private menagerie.  I am the Keeper of this place.  Upon my return, we shall begin the task of minimizing the damage already done to your corporeal form.  Saffron, feverfew, and nettles will be an adequate start, I believe.  I advise you to rest.  For myself, I am in danger of being late for a dinner date and may not return for many hours."<br><br>As the creature's footsteps faded with distance, she realized belatedly that the words had been spoken, with no trace of slur or accent, in the precise formal tongue of the Feir'Dal.<br><br>***<br><br>T'Veren watched the members of the High Lord's retinue assemble in the dining room with a jaundiced interest, focusing most of his attention on the two most recent additions:  the young "lord" Rileaus and the menial Keeper.<br><br>It was T'Ere's habit to take his evening meals, when possible, with both his family and those he considered chief among his servants; a constant, physical reminder of who their master truly was.<br><br>"Leave a clerk too long unattended and he will begin to believe that the monies he handles are his own," T'Ere had once remarked and T'Veren agreed however, where the High Lord wanted to be seen, his 'right hand' preferred to see.<br><br>The High Lord and his family sat behind the long banquet table that fronted the dining room, facing the perpendicular rows of lower tables where the menials supped.  T'Veren was seated at the Lord's right, a position of trust and honor but, more importantly to T'Veren, a position which afforded him full view of the dining hall's occupants.  While the staff looked up, presumably with gratitude and adoration, T'Veren looked down, measuring their motions and glances, studying them for lapses in control, knowing looks of shared meaning, and hints of disloyalty or conspiracy.  More than once, T'Veren's surveillance had lead to the undoing of a plot against or within the house.<br><br>T'Veren's position within the House T'Enel was at once uniquely secure and unenviable.  T'Veren was T'Ere's cousin on his mother's side, granting him all the privileges of nobility but placing him outside the line of succession.  He would never hold a position higher than T'Ere's second.  To a different man, this would be a source of constant frustration but T'Veren's personality was perfectly matched to the role.  He enjoyed an unusual level of freedom for a member of a noble house, the satisfaction of a job done well, and an increasingly powerful house:  fulfillment enough of his ambitions.  That T'Ere trusted him above all others was his greatest reward and, among the paranoid suspicions and constant plotting of the Teir'Dal nobility, the greatest freedom.  A shared childhood and a few disgraceful incidents carefully hidden insured the bond.<br><br>"What do you think of the boy?" T'Ere asked, leaning close to be heard.<br><br>"Typical:  cowed, weak, petulant, eminently malleable--treat him well, indulge his whim and coddle him a bit and he'll never grow enough of a spine to become a threat.  Be cautious however; no one throws a temper tantrum like a spoiled child."<br><br>"What about loyalty, Veren?  Or at least control?"<br><br>"Hard to say.  We have years before it becomes an issue.  I think the Lady Even'gel may prove to be an asset in that department.  She seems quite taken with the young man and he is going to be desperate for the emotional security of a parental figure not directly related to the death of his family."<br><br>T'Ere snorted.  "In other words, he'll always hate me but I can probably rule him indirectly through my wife.  You're a cold one, Veren, but probably right again.  Even' has taken to doting over the whelp as bad as she does that damned dog."<br><br>T'Veren remained pointedly silent, disguising his discomfort with a mouthful of food.<br><br>T'Ere appeared not to notice.  "What of our ragged little Keeper?"<br><br>T'Veren chewed slowly as he studied the Keeper across the room.  The menial had dressed for the dinner as best he could.  His tattered leather mask had been replaced with a polished metal one and soiled rags exchanged for a more colorful motley of clean ones.  Replaced, too, were the heavy, soiled  bandages covering his left hand, now surprisingly white with new wrappings.  As T'Veren watched, the Keeper ate sparingly:  pulling his food apart into small pieces with his good hand, not always an easy task, and then slipping the bits beneath the mask.<br><br>"I don't trust him," T'Veren replied at length.  "I'd like to know why the Mayong maimed him before sending him to us."<br><br>"His face, you mean?"<br><br>"No, but that as well.  I was referring to his hand.  The way he eats, the foot he leads with as he walks, all of his body language, the way he holds his weight as he stands--every indicator is that he's left handed, now obviously maimed.  And he hums?"<br><br>"He what?"<br><br>"Hums, sings, things like that.  Not loudly or often but enough that I've noticed it."<br><br>T'Enel popped a morsel into his mouth and spoke around it.  "No harm in that.  Innoruuk himself has an orchestra."<br><br>"But the Mayong doesn't.  He hates music, made it illegal in all of Mistmoore."<br><br>"Maybe that's your answer.  On the maiming, I mean."<br><br>"Maybe.  I still don't trust him.  He carries himself wrong for a servant."  <br><br>"How so?"<br><br>"Head up, back straight, shoulders square.  He watches his surroundings instead of his feet.  He's humble enough in public but his body language screams the opposite.  No, that one is no servant."<br><br>"Ah-ha!" interjected T'Enel, thrusting his fork into the air for emphasis.   "There I see a flaw in your reasoning, old friend.  You forget, he is a master of the animals.  He walks like one of our generals, does he not?"<br><br>"My point.  He walks exactly like a general or a priest, not a menial."<br><br>"Ah, Veren, a leader must walk as a leader.  He must show no weakness and he must do so naturally.  It is not something that can be disguised or faked.  He can not move as a servant.  We see this in the leaders of our army; why should we not expect it in the general of our warrens?  He is our animal general."<br><br>"Not exactly the same thing, m'lord."  T'Veren watched as the Keeper pulled a portion of bone free of its meat and inspected it closely.  Apparently dissatisfied, the Keeper set it aside and returned to worrying apart his meal.<br><br>"On this, you borrow worry.  Besides, for so long as he keeps our 'guest' alive, he can walk however he chooses.  Mark my words, cousin:  Man or beast, leadership is a constant."<br><br>***<br><br>Visibility was good through the hilly forest in the spring.  It had been fall when Carezzia had last seen the Order's guildhouse.  The winter had passed during her travels and imprisonment and the brisk chill of the moist early morning was a welcome sensation.<br><br>The building seemed smaller than she remembered it and it did not seem to have weathered well through the winter storms.  The roof seemed to sag and the walls looked as if they leaned inward against each other.  No matter, the familiar surroundings were a welcome sight.<br><br>It was as she descended the last rolling hillside toward the building that the feeling of unease began to settle on her, like a stranger within her own home, a butterfly straining against the shell of its cocoon.  Her breath quickened and she look nervously around.  The bear, Marlowe, had vanished sometime during her descent and her cat had loped off on business of its own, apparently undisturbed.  She struggled to cast off the shadow of claustrophobia and crossed the last of the distance to the house.<br><br>The building was empty, at least from appearances, and had been that way for some time.  Carezzia was used to the vacancy of the guildhouse.  Most of those who lived within spent the majority of their lives on the road, but this was a strangely different emptiness; surreal and dreamlike, a sealed kind of empty, a sort of…<br><br>/sacrosanct…<br>…sepulturic/<br><br>The voices had been silent since she had left Toxxulia and she shivered.<br><br>/do not be afraid…<br>…know fear/<br>/reality is your intent to perceive…<br>…it is only real if you choose it/<br><br>She placed a hand on the door, noticing deep scars in the wood of the frame.  The door sagged on its hinges, swollen in the damp of the morning.  The wood elf had to struggle, almost comically, to force it open.  The brisk chill of the forest deepened into a true cold and even with the morning light spilling in, the building felt dark, permanently tinged with grey.  Despite her concerns, Carezzia pulled the door closed behind her.  It seemed…proper.<br><br>She expected her footsteps to echo in the hallways.  Instead, there was only a muffled shuffling as she moved, which, to her chagrin, grated even worse on her nerves.  She decided to forego a visit to her room and proceed directly to her goal:  the battered desk in the council room.  As she turned away from the passage to the member's quarters, a bright pin-point flash of silver caught her eyes.<br><br>Captivated by the glimmer, Carezzia sprinted to it, searching the blank wall where she had seen it.  Rough cut oaken planking stood mutely before her, its only abnormality a blackened knothole just below shoulder height.  Stymied by the anomaly, she turned again toward the doors of the council chamber. <br><br>Carezzia raised her hand to press open the double doors and paused.  The very room was a mystery, a place long denied her and a place she had never felt comfortable.  It was a pot brewing with tension for brief moments and then drained empty for weeks on end, the raw emotion left behind, hanging in the air, sealed within these doors.<br><br>In her experience, only one man had seemed immune to the room's sanctity.  She thought on what the Erudian had told her of the builders of the house.  Perhaps that was why Descourge had never seemed phased by the atmosphere of the room, because he predated the council, because he had helped to build the room.  More likely, she reasoned, because he knew that this single room would give him the most privacy.<br><br>If the old druid had been one of the builders…Carezzia dug through the few belongings she had recovered, searching for the prints of the guildhouse the fairy had given her.  Finding them, she sat in the hall and unrolled them.  Studying them, she traced the outline of rooms with her fingers, searching for what she would not find.<br><br>Both the Ancient and the Fey had specifically referred to Descourge's room within the guildhouse but, according to the prints and her own explorations, it was flatly impossible for that room to be in the building.  Frustrated and perplexed, she returned the prints to their tube and stood, again facing the double doors.<br><br>There was a deep scar in one of the door panels, a hole as if something had been driven into it.  Whatever had happened, no effort had been made to repair or hide the wound.  She pressed her fingertips against it, feeling the edges of the wood, and found a memory.<br><br>A lifetime ago, she had found Azimuth standing similarly before these doors, wearing a melancholy look with his single eye staring forward into the past at some personal remembrance.  "It is a great irony to me," he had whispered upon her approach, "that the argument took place, not here, but in the Theatre of the Tranquil.  I wonder if he appreciates the melodrama."  Carezzia had been young then, and new to the house.  She had withdrawn quietly, confused and a little frightened.  Now she wished the wizard were here, or at least that she had questioned him further.<br><br>She was stalling.  To her chagrin, she realized she was truly afraid.  Before she could lose her nerve, the elf shoved open the doors.<br><br>


