<td width="83%" class="lighttable">
<br />
<font class="post">
The Lady Even'gel clutched her husband's arm and tried in vain to keep her voice from rising to a whining pitch.  "You've spent two days away before the Council and all of dinner you ignored me."<br><br>T'Enel pulled away with a jerk.  "I had to speak with Veren at dinner.  I've lost two days and the work of running this house does not stop when I am absent.  I have matters to see to."<br><br>"You always have matters to see to.  Let someone else do them.  Why did you even attack House Rileaus?  Am I not enough for you?  You have to always have some intrigue to amuse you."<br><br>"Even'gel, I do not have time for this!"  T'Enel snapped.<br><br>"You never have time for me.  Ever since Garet died…"<br><br>"Never speak that name to me!"<br><br>"He was our son!"<br><br>"He's dead, woman!  Let it go!"<br><br>"How can I?  You avoid me, you haven't touched me for years.  Am I repulsive?  Is that it?  You've found another, more attractive woman to replace me?"<br><br>"You are hysterical!"  the High Lord shouted, shoving back her clinging, reaching hands.  "See to your dog and the boy."<br><br>"Rene."<br><br>"Rene, whatever.  I have a house to run and I could do with some help for a change instead of your incessant crying!"  T'Enel stormed from her room, slamming the door behind him.<br><br>"Maid!"  Even'gel cried out in distress and collapsed, sobbing, to the floor.<br><br>"M'lady, are you…"<br><br>"Bring me a cordial.  I must have a tonic for my nerves," she fluttered, wringing her hands as the girl rushed to her side.  "I shall go to my garden.  Bring me the hound and summon the young Lord Rene to meet me as well."<br><br>***<br><br>T'Enel burst into the study, slamming open the door and startling T'Veren from the ledgers he had been examining.  "I swear that woman will drive me mad.  I indulge her every whim and still she clings to me like a drowning child.  Does she think I've no better use for my time than holding her hand and lisping poetry to her?"<br><br>"She is your wife, T'Enel," replied T'Veren curtly, flustered from his usual composure by the suddenness of the interruption.<br><br>"Do I sense disapproval?  You agree with her?"<br><br>T'Veren recognized the hidden danger of the temper which lurked beneath the question.  The High Lord was in no mood for honest advice.  "I simply state that when you chose her as your bride, you wanted a woman who would be dependant upon you and easy to--well--control.  You wished no concerns regarding her loyalties.  Her overly emotional outbursts are merely a symptom of these more desirable qualities."<br><br>T'Enel hesitated, uncertain if he had been somehow insulted, then shrugged.  "As you say, cousin.  It is a passing bother.  Ha!  She even accused me of having a mistress."<br><br>You do, T'Veren thought; your revenge is your lover now.  Then, aloud, "I fear we face a long night.  These records from Rileaus are going to take some time to review."<br><br>***<br><br>Rene Rileaus, ward of House T'Enel, approached his new mother timidly, disturbed by her obvious distress.<br><br>"You…you've been crying," he said softly.<br><br>She turned a wan smile toward him.  "It is all right, child.  We just…we had a slight argument."<br><br>"Did he strike you?"<br><br>"To my very heart.  He does me such wrong yet I love him so.  I only wish…I do not want him ever to be hurt but, if only he could feel what I feel, if he could know the pain of losing the very thing you love the most as his estrangement does to me."<br><br>Rene nodded, silently thinking of his own family, slain utterly at T'Ere's command.<br><br>Even'gel sighed, the sound catching in her breast like a sob.  "Have the maids bring me another cordial.  Oh my nerves.  I shant sleep again tonight, I'm sure."<br><br>***<br><br>A new smell, a steam of garlic and onions wafting through her darkness, lured Kathrin back to awareness and she moaned painfully as her mind crossed again the threshold back to her body.<br><br>"Drink it slowly," instructed the Keeper, again in precise and formal Feir'Dal. "I've a headache and no desire to clean your regurgitation."  He pressed a warm, earthenware mug into her hands.<br><br>In reply, she threw the container toward the sound of his voice.  She heard the crock shatter and her Keeper hissed in frustration.  "Drink it yourself," she growled.<br><br>"If you do not take sustenance, you will die."<br><br>"Then let me die.  It is my only escape from this torment."<br><br>"For, if you were to escape physically, you would endanger your children.  Better that your knowledges and secrets die with you than T'Ere should ever have a chance to spy upon you unawares.  This, I understand.  The druid Quill said much the same to me before he died."<br><br>Kathrin forced herself into a roughly sitting position and opened her eyes to see the Keeper staring at her appraisingly, head cocked to one side like a bird, gauging her reaction.<br><br>"How do you know of Quildluane?" she demanded.<br><br>"Yes," the creature replied as if hearing a different question.  "I have taken steps to insure that we will not be overheard or spied upon.  The rats themselves stand sentry for us and the arcane wards placed to prevent your possible escape also function quite well to prevent scrying as well.  Thank you for your concern."<br><br>"I said…"<br><br>"I heard what you said!" the Keeper snapped.  "Next you will remind me that Quill was a bard by training and then you will ask me how he died.  None of these questions have merit and I've no desire to banter words with you."<br><br>"Then leave me die in peace!"<br><br>"No.  Your death at this juncture serves no purpose.  To die now is to throw aside your last weapon against your enemy.  Die on your own timetable, not his.  Now drink."<br><br>"I threw it away."<br><br>"And I have a dozen more prepared.  I have dealt with childish wood elves before."<br><br>"Childish?  I'm old enough…"<br><br>"To have grandchildren!  Have you thought about that?  It's bigger than just you!"  The Keeper loomed over Kathrin, his eyes intent and his tone angry.  "Yes, grandchildren.  You've been down here a long time and the stakes are a lot higher.  Now you make up your mind:  risk all of them for the sake of your pride or shut up and drink the blasted broth.  Eat, rest, and then go back to dying if you're so set on it but act like an adult.  Act like the woman Arthur Majialenne married; the woman who gave up everything, even her children, to stop T'Ere the first time!"<br><br>Fear and anger fought for supremacy in Kathrin's mind.  This creature knew more of her family and her past than even T'Ere did.  "Who are you?" she asked.<br><br>The Keeper sighed and the tension drained from his voice.  "I am no one.  I am tired and I am weary.  Just drink the broth."<br><br>"I do not like you," she replied sullenly, accepting the new mug presented to her.<br><br>"Don't need to."<br><br>"But I will trust you…for now."  She lifted the container and drank, small sips on a long empty stomach.<br><br>"Don't trust me.  I have my own goals in this.  We share a common enemy."<br><br>"T'Enel."<br><br>"T'Ere."<br><br>***<br><br>The doors to the council chamber swung open at her touch, silent and smooth, very different from the outer door.  Not much had changed.  The large stone fireplace was empty save for chill ashes and no new timber had been laid within.  The oval table in the room's center, surrounded by chairs, was marred only by a spire of obsidian which curved slightly, one blade-like end driven into the table and the other end sharply snapped off.  The room's final furnishing was the battered roll-top desk in the shadowed corner of the room, occluded by the fireplace, closed and locked.<br><br>Carezzia stepped into the room and a chill danced across the nape of her neck.  She jumped and spun to stare at the empty hallway behind.  Chiding herself for her nervousness, she crossed the threshold into the chamber and pulled the doors closed behind her.  She walked cautiously to the edge of the desk.<br><br>There was a high-backed wooden slat chair at the desk but she chose to stand.  The desk had no drawers, only a shallow tray, recessed a bit below the writing surface.  The roll-top shutter was down, a build-in lock the obvious match to the key she had been given, and the flat of the desk's crest held no trinkets, merely dust.<br><br>She reached to pull out the tray and her fingers brushed cold metal.  She knelt to see a long, curved scabbard was fastened to the underside of the tray with short leather straps and brads--hidden and empty.  Again the incongruity struck her:  here in the guild's most inner sanctum was a place to secret a weapon.<br><br>The tray itself was awash with feathers.  Worn and broken remnants of a half-hundred quills filled the tray to overflowing, drifting, now freed, to the floor about the desk like an avian rainfall.  Smothered beneath their quilt, she noted other bits of debris:  the broken shaft and blade of a pen-knife, an empty ink pot, fragments of bone and leather, scraps of parchment crushed into balls, splintered birch bark, partially chewed.<br><br>She pulled one of the larger balls of parchment free and unfolded it.  Crabbed writing covered both sides in at least three different inks and a dozen different languages.  The scrap was so heavily used that she could barely make out individual words.  Cross-hatched notes added even more chaos to the scribblings.  Shopping lists and cooking recipes, traveling directions and contextless lines of doggerel--all these things and more were woven across each other upon the page.<br><br>Carezzia laid the paper on the council table and then, finding no other way up, climbed onto the table, stretching to reach the lamps hung above it.  After lighting them and a troublesome period of trimming wicks and adjusting shutters, she coaxed the room into a comfortable illumination.  The light brightened her mood as well as her surroundings and she was smiling by the time she hopped back to the floor.  The reflection of light from the black spar in the table captivated her and she watched the twinkling motes of color dance across the obsidian surface.<br><br>/beauty in all things…<br>…easily distracted/<br>/appreciative and artistic…<br>…prey/<br><br>She turned her attention again to the scrap of parchment, now easier to discern in the light and, turning it at an angle, found what seemed to be a discarded list of tasks.  She read the portions she could make out and smiled at the glimpses of the personality behind its author.<br><br>"Rescrap bear pelt.  Amend Charter.  Patch Tunic.  Talk to Tony re-Kane.  Finish trans. on Tesch Mas scrolls.  Eat.  Talk to Millers re-carrots.  Teleport Monk.  Repair porch.  See Misty re-Paw, sick child?  Kill Goonda.  Find missing boot.  Talk to T/K re-alliance CoV/fey.  Establish Senate.  Apologize to Oz, again re-eye.  Find figurehead for empire.  Replace broken lock, get extra key made.  Kill Aelric."<br><br>At the last item she laughed aloud, then again harder when she saw, obviously added later, an arrow moving the item to a significantly higher priority on the list.  She returned the parchment to the tray, crammed the feathers down as best she could, and shoved it hurriedly closed.<br><br>She was tired from the road and the tension of her day but it was still early and she felt more at ease now.  The kindling box by the fireplace was full and a few large sticks of wood were lodged beside it.  It did not take her long to build a respectable fire to ward off the chill and she ate a quick lunch from the stores of her pack.  Fortified and warmed, she decided to lay in a supply of wood for the fire and begin her investigation of the desk in earnest.  After her findings in the tray, it promised to be a most interesting endeavor indeed.<br><br>It was only as she licked sticky berry juice from her fingers that she realized she was guilty of the same disregard for her surroundings that she had previously found so mysterious in her predecessor. <br><br>Predecessor:  where had that word sprung from?  In truth, she knew next to nothing about the elder druid and what she did know raised more questions in turn.<br><br>/mentor…<br>…guide/<br>/prototype…<br>…father/<br><br>"No," she protested aloud.  "My father was Arthur Majialenne.  He died when I was a baby.  The bard Quildluane raised me.  I have no connection to…"  Her voice trailed to silence.  She could not deny a sense of kinship to the Ancient, a feeling of shared perspectives, comparable ideals.  Once again, an uncomfortable confusion began to gnaw its way into her mind.<br><br>"Wood for the fire," she announced purposefully and headed for the outside.  There should still be a plentiful supply in the wood bin alongside the porch and she would only need a few armloads to see her through the afternoon.<br><br>She exited the building into the frosty darkness of night.  The stars were clear in the cloudless sky and the moon was well into its assent.  She was suddenly dizzy and sick to her stomach.  "It's not possible.  It can't…"<br><br>/after-effects…<br>…dilation/<br>/residual magics…<br>…asymmetric lag/<br>/self-correcting time…<br>… linearity is illusory anyhow/<br><br>Carezzia fled back into the guildhouse, slamming doors behind her until she was huddled before the fireplace.<br><br>"Tomorrow," she told herself.  "I'll deal with it all tomorrow."  Eventually she fell into a fitful sleep, the baying of wolves her lullaby. <br>


