<td width="83%" class="lighttable">
<br />
<font class="post">
It was not until her second crock of the thin broth that Kathrin felt the lassitude spreading through her body. The Keeper had made a crude firepit of loose stones alongside her pallet and had built up a modest flame, and it was to this she had at first attributed her growing comfort. As her legs began to numb and her eyes refused to focus, she knew her increasing languor was due to most than warmth and nourishment.<br><br>"You've drugged me," she said, her voice flat. "I trusted you and you drugged me."<br><br>The Keeper prodded the fire with the toe of his boot and commented as if to no one in particular. "I'll have to cut more peat if we're to keep a fire tomorrow. Technically, I introduced an herbal sophoric into the broth; I did not, specifically, drug anyone. Nevertheless, your concerns are misplaced. I shall have to examine you to determine the extent of injury done by your years of tight captivity. This will necessitate the extension and palpitation of those joints and muscles long atrophied. Though necessary, the process will most certainly be quite painful. Ergo, by inducing a seditious agent into your system, I provide, not betrayal, but expedient courtesy." <br><br>"Fancy reasons to justify simple deceit. Why not tell me and avoid the lying?"<br><br>"Lying? You wound me but I forgive you. Had I told you, would you have agreed to this, as you put it, drugging?"<br><br>"No."<br><br>"Of course. And since such a thing must be done, I would then have been forced to contrive some deliberate deception to achieve the same result. Thus, by avoiding the discussion, I have avoided the necessity of misleading you."<br><br>"You lie pretty," muttered Kathrin, and surrendered to sleep.<br><br>***<br><br>There was no rest in Carezzia's sleep. It was as if, in her dreams, she were a ribbon of cloth, blown in a swirling wind, turning about in circles and knotting in upon herself. The greyness of unseeing that she twisted through, like a kite's tail caught in a storm, was overshadowed by the fairy, never seen but felt--intuited, leaving impressions stronger than mere visions.<br><br>These were not the small sprites and flittering sylphs common to the woods; they were not ever the regal gentility of the Princess Joleena. These fey were something older, something darker, veiled glimpses of the greater powers, the ancient fairy blood of before the Sundering, before Teir and Feir'Dal. These shadows of antiquity, of sylvan power long diluted and forgotten, these hauntings in her dreams were the Fairy Court in its glory; the elder spirits who slept, themselves outside of time, whose dreams her own mind barely brushed, the ancient spirits of the land; and they frightened her as she felt herself suffocating, drawn moth-like to the blazing intensity of their dreaming visions.<br><br>A storm broke within the clouding of her mind and she was free, racing away from seductive delusions of fallen glory, flying without form through crystal space. Below her stretched a road which was a river outside of time. The river was the flowing of the years, a road from birth to death of all moments of all things, the path of all existence, the penultimate journey unending. The road which was the river was paved with stone, smooth brown pebbles of the river bed of time; and each stone, a moment, a memory, a prophecy, each stone a step in the journey of creation's existence. This was the power of the ancient fey: to stand at the river's banks and see time, at once still and passing--predestination and free will reconciled as a river, choosing its own way yet always choosing the way set before it.<br><br>As she slept, tossing and turning, whimpering and struggling to surface into wakefulness before she drowned, Carezzia's hand closed upon the fragments of the smooth brown stone given her by the fey--the moment of eternal memory plucked from the river of the street of time, the Fairy Court's gift that she might understand the Ancient of Days--and as she did, her nightmares passed, her breathing calmed, and she slipped into a deep and dreamless slumber.<br><br>***<br><br>In the waning hours after midnight, while most of the House T'Enel slept, others remained awake, lying abed, thoughts drifting between schemes and fantasies.<br><br>Rene felt no grief at the loss of his family. His father was an absent figurehead and, by all accounts, a fool and a sensate. His mother turned a blind eye to her husband's peccadilloes and ruled her household with an iron fist; children and servants alike were merely pawns in her games. His sister had existed solely as glorified chattel, a marriageable commodity to expand his mother's web. As for his older brother, that singular impediment to his own claim upon the inheritance of the household--T'Ere had saved Rene the trouble of killing the bullying braggart himself.<br><br>Even so, Rene held no love for T'Ere. The slight against House Rileaus would have to be avenged for pride's sake and the boy had little doubt that T'Ere, if not already, soon would move to bleed the rival house of the bulk of its power and assets. It was not unlikely that, after a time, T'Ere would arrange for a tragic accident to remove the sole heir and absorb the other house entirely. He had time, he knew; T'Ere would have to be patient. His enemies on the Council of Nobles were too many and too strong for T'Ere to give them an excuse to move openly against him but Rene would have to reckon with him in time.<br><br>Of them all, only the Lady Even'gel had shown him any kindness, an affection he intended to return and encourage. He would need allies within the House T'Enel and the High Lord's wife was a significant one. With the possible exception of T'Veren, she alone might have the power to shield Rene from T'Ere. As for T'Veren, Rene saw only the instrument of Rileaus' destruction. T'Ere had given the orders but T'Veren had carried them out. In Rene's mind, T'Ere was a distant threat but T'Veren was an immediate enemy.<br><br>The young man's thoughts ranged from straight-forward violence to subtle betrayal--but they were the things of hopeful imagination. Only one thing stood apart in his mind as having real potential for the vengeance he sought, an insight presented by Even'gel herself: to take from T'Ere that which he truly loved. But what it was, what specifically would strike the deepest, Rene did not yet know. House, power, family--which of these were not important to T'Ere? Rene would have to learn, and soon; T'Ere would not wait forever before moving against him.<br><br>These things the man-child Rene considered as he drifted into more childish dreams of glorious battle and bloody revenge.<br><br>***<br><br>Muted speech stirred Kathrin from her envenomed stupor. The concoction's effects were still heavy in her system and it was a struggle to remain awake.<br><br>"I do not accept this. There must be alternatives." The Keeper was speaking, his voice low but is tone intense, angry. "You teach me to hope in the face of all odds. You show me miracles in all things. You train me to find options when none can be seen. All this and now you tell me 'No', to fulfill my role and bow to the inevitable? I will not accept it!"<br><br>If a reply was made, she did not hear it and, after a moment, the Keeper spoke again. "I do not challenge your wisdom. I challenge your hypocrisy. You once held accountability as a virtue, has that changed? Is it no longer seemly for a priest to think for himself? To expect the gods to abide by the precepts which they teach?" The Keeper spoke louder now, his voice resentful. <br><br>Kathrin shifted on her pallet and forced an eyelid open, trying to catch a glimpse of the conversants before exhaustion overwhelmed her again. The Keeper stood some distance away from the dying fire, his back to her, facing outward into the darkness of the cavern. His cowl was pulled back and his mask held in his left hand. The only feature she could discern was a cascade of wiry white hair that fell well below the his shoulders. Of the one he spoke with, there was no sign.<br><br>Another pause and the Keeper sighed and looked to shrink back in upon himself in defeat. "It is not given that I should know all things," he said finally. "I must accept the Hunters' Peace on this matter."<br><br>As she succumbed again to blackness, Kathrin imagined that she saw motion in the darkness and the shadowed silhouette of wide-spread antlers. Her last conscious thought was surprise that she had not earlier noticed that the Keeper's boots were, in color, red.<br>


